  "text": "PL are degraded through two main pathways of hydrolysis and/ or oxidation. Hydrolysis usually occurs in the presence of water to produce lysophospholipids and free fatty acids. Lysophospholipids are subsequently degraded to glycerophospho compounds as the end product of PL hydrolysis. In addition, PL hydrolysis is catalyzed under either basic or acid conditions [CITATION_1] . On the other hand, the PL degradation via oxidation of its fatty acids is similar to other lipids. There are several proposed mechanisms for lipid oxidation, namely, lipid autoxidation, photoxidation, and enzymatic or nonenzymatic oxidation. The discussion of photoxidation and enzymatic oxidation for marine PL is beyond the scope of this review paper. Therefore, the discussion of this part will mainly focus on autoxidation of marine PL with special emphasis on n-3 LC PUFA (EPA and DHA).",
